A moving video shows the moment a captured Russian soldier breaks down in tears on a video call to his mother after surrendering to Ukrainians. The young man is seen drinking tea and eating a pasty as he is comforted by locals who offer him a phone so he can tell his family he is safe. The young prisoner of war blows kisses as his mother answers, and bursts into tears as soon as he sees her. A Ukrainian woman pats him on the head and says down the phone: ‘Don’t worry Natasha, he’s alive and well. You will get a call later.’ For the latest updates on the Russia-Ukraine war, visit our live blog:  Russia-Ukraine live As the man is looked after by locals, a male voice off camera is heard saying in Ukrainian: ‘These young men, it’s not their fault. They don’t know why they are here. They are using old maps, they are lost.’ {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"VideoObject","name":"Metro.co.uk","duration":"T1M42S","thumbnailUrl":"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2022/03/03/07/54893593-0-image-a-14_1646292130545.jpg","uploadDate":"2022-03-03T07:22:18+0000","description":"Moving footage on Twitter shows a Russian solider who had surrendered to the Ukrainian people receiving a welcoming reception as he is offered food and drink.","contentUrl":"https://videos.metro.co.uk/video/met/2022/03/03/5349013846632841655/480x270_MP4_5349013846632841655.mp4","height":270,"width":480}  To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web
