                            video For the latest updates on the Russia-Ukraine war, visit our live blog: Russia-Ukraine live The video has gone viral in both Ukraine and Russia, with people praising the compassion the Ukrainians showed to the man who has been ordered to invade their country. The footage emerged as the Ukrainian Ministry of Defence said Russian mothers could could come to Kyiv and collect their sons who had been taken prisoner. The ministry has provided an email address and phone numbers that can be used to find out if a soldier was ‘in captivity or had died’. Explaining the decision, one official said: ‘We Ukrainians, unlike Putin’s fascists, do not fight mothers and their captive children. We are waiting for you in Kyiv!’. Ukraine’s Deputy Prime Minister Iryna Vereshchuk has also asked for the International Red Cross to help repatriate the dead bodies of Russian soldiers. She said: ‘We call upon Russians again to make it so that there are fewer bodies of your sons, of your men, otherwise there will be thousands of them. I say it again, victory will be ours.’ Reports suggest that many tired and demoralised Russian forces are either fleeing battle or surrendering to Ukraine. The besieged country’s fierce resistance has been credited with stalling Moscow’s advance on capital city Kyiv. Last night, Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky claimed the morale of Vladimir Putin’s Russian forces is ‘constantly deteriorating’ and that his forces have so-far killed 9,000 invaders. In a powerful address, he praised the ‘heroism’ of his people for breaking Putin’s plans to seize Kyiv and topple the democratically-elected government. {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"VideoObject","name":"Metro.co.uk","duration":"T3M6S","thumbnailUrl":"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2022/02/28/19/54768033-0-image-a-13_1646075239763.jpg","uploadDate":"2022-02-28T19:08:11+0000","description":"The Ukrainian ambassador to the United Nations, Sergiy Kyslytsya, started his address